<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.sciam.com/article.cfm?chanID=sa003&amp;articleID=000CF6C6-ABE0-1DDE-A838809EC588F2D7">ScientificAmerican.com</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
The recent Leonid meteor shower gave skygazers a chance to observe pieces of space debris meeting their demise as they collided with the earth's atmosphere at high speeds. Most of the streaks on display during the Leonid shower are just specks of cometary dust and hence pose little risk to observers on the ground. But explosions of much larger asteroids high in the atmosphere can cause considerable damage to our planet. A study published in the current issue of the journal Nature calculates just how likely such collisions are. The good news? The findings suggest that 10-megaton explosions from objects about 50 meters wide will occur about one third as often as previously believed.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 477<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/25/02 5:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=81.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Near-Earth Asteroid Explosions.</span><hr size=1> In a way though this news could be bad.  It might give politicians and the public an excuse to turn their backs on programs meant to detect asteroids and protect us from them.  Politicians and the public tend to be heavily influenced by statistics and they might let their guard down.  Such a discovery also has the potential to set back the development of space technology in general.  Don't get me wrong, this is good news if the numbers are accurate but I fear the possible impact on space development could be negative.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2582<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/25/02 9:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=81.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Near-Earth Asteroid Explosions.</span><hr size=1> Absolutely. It's going to be little comfort knowing the possibility of an impact was only one third as high as previously thought when we watch it happen. The chances of getting struck by lightning is slim but people get hit every year. With an asteroid impact millions could die. In just one unlucky roll of the dice you get perhaps tsunami's, earthquakes, atmospheric dust on a magnitude sufficient to trigger an ice age, uncontrollable firestorms and trigger happy generals starting WW3. But hey, what are the chances. Only a third as high as previosly thought it seems. No need to worry about defense systems. It probably wont happen right? I think we deserve whatever happens to us. Any species this stupid belongs with the Dodo. Sorry if I sound like one of those human extinction cults but the small mindedness of politicians makes me want to drop a nuke on congress. Nothing short of thermonuclear weaponry could penetrate their thick skulls. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=whitestar60>whitestar60</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 54<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/26/02 8:18 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.